# UI/UX Design Principles — Apply to Every Page

## TRUST HIERARCHY (Merchant Processing)

Every page that mentions payments, processing, or fees must include **at least one trust signal** in the visible viewport: the compliance disclaimer, a payment network logo row (Visa / Mastercard / Amex / Discover / ACH), or the **"NMI Certified Partner"** badge.

- Trust signals must appear **BEFORE** the primary CTA, never after.
- A merchant must feel safe before they are asked to act.

## VISUAL HIERARCHY — THE 3-SECOND RULE

Every page must answer within ~3 seconds for a first-time visitor:

1. **What is this?** → **H1**
2. **Who is it for?** → One subheading or bullet list
3. **What do I do next?** → One primary CTA (`btn-accent` or `btn-primary`)

Never put two **primary** CTAs side by side — one is always primary, one is always secondary (`btn-outline`).

## COLOR USAGE RULES

- **`bg-brand-dark`** (`#0c3a30`): high-authority moments — hero, pricing, testimonials, final CTA. **Maximum 3 dark sections per page.**
- **`bg-brand-light`** (`#edf1ee`): neutral content — feature lists, how-it-works, comparisons.
- **`bg-brand-card`** (`#fffaeb`) and **`bg-white`**: cards, forms, content that needs to breathe.
- **`bg-brand-accent`** (`#9edd05`): **NEVER** as a section background. Only badges, highlights, active states, and **`btn-accent`**. Overusing accent destroys conversion power.
- **Never** more than **2 dark sections back-to-back** without a light section between them.

## TYPOGRAPHY HIERARCHY

- **H1:** `font-display` (Outfit), `text-4xl` minimum, **one per page**, always above the fold.
- **H2:** `font-display`, `text-3xl`, section headings only.
- **H3:** `font-display`, `text-xl`, card headings and subsections.
- **Body:** Inter Tight, `text-base` or `text-lg`, color `var(--paragraph)`.
- **Section labels:** always **`.section-label`** — never invent a new pill/badge style.
- **`gradient-text`:** **maximum one instance per page** — reserved for the most important H2 on that page.

## SPACING AND LAYOUT

- Full-width sections use **`.section-ptb`** — never custom `py-*` on sections.
- Content max-width: **`max-w-7xl`** for standard sections; **`max-w-4xl`** for centered text-heavy sections (FAQ, legal, blog).
- **Mobile padding:** always **`px-6` minimum** on section containers — never less.
- Cards use **`.charm-card`** — do not invent new card styles with ad-hoc shadows/borders.
- **Touch targets:** interactive elements (buttons, links, accordion triggers, nav items) **`min-h-[44px]`** minimum.

## CONVERSION FLOW — MARKETING PAGE STRUCTURE

Every marketing page should follow this **section order**:

1. Hero (dark bg, H1, primary CTA, trust badge)
2. Social proof OR feature differentiator (light bg)
3. Core product/feature explanation (white or light bg)
4. Objection handler — pricing, FAQ, or comparison (any bg)
5. Final CTA section (dark bg, two buttons: primary + secondary)
6. Footer

- **Never** end a marketing page without a **dark CTA section** above the footer.
- **Never** put FAQ or pricing as the **last** content section — always follow with a CTA.

## FORM AND APPLICATION RULES

- Standard input pattern: `<label>` with `htmlFor`, matching `id` on the control, `aria-describedby` for hints, `aria-invalid` for errors.
- Multi-step forms: **progressive disclosure** — **maximum 4 fields per step**.
- Errors: **`role="alert"`**, inline below the field — **not** only a toast.
- Submit buttons: loading state (spinner + disabled) while processing.
- **Never** use placeholder text as a substitute for a label.

## PHOTOGRAPHY AND IMAGERY

- **Hero:** real business owner in context (barbershop, salon, boutique, restaurant) — not abstract tech-only imagery.
- **Product screenshots:** device mockup or styled card frame — not raw floating screenshots.
- **Alt text:** descriptive for meaningful images; **`alt=""`** only for decorative images with **`aria-hidden="true"`** on ornaments if needed.
- **Aspect ratios:** hero photos `aspect-video` or `aspect-[4/3]`; profile photos `aspect-square` with `rounded-full`.

## ACCESSIBILITY — NON-NEGOTIABLE

- Exactly **one H1** per page.
- Non-native interactive widgets: **`role`**, **`aria-*`**, and **keyboard** behavior.
- **Color alone** must never be the only way information is conveyed — pair with icon or text.
- Animation classes (`animate-float`, `animate-rotation`, etc.) live in **`globals.css`** with **`prefers-reduced-motion`** — **do not** add new animations outside `globals.css`.
- **Never** use **`.reveal`** on **static server components** — it requires client JS to add `.visible` and can leave content invisible.

## CHARM CARDS vs CHARM PAYMENTS — TONE SPLIT

- **Charm Payments:** professional, authoritative, numbers-forward. Specifics ("$16,600 annual savings", "24-hour approval", "99.99% uptime"). Tone: trusted local partner.
- **Charm Cards:** energetic, lifestyle-forward, identity-focused. Outcomes ("clients tap your chair", "your whole crew", "no app needed"). Tone: modern tool for hustlers.
- **Never mix tones on one page.** Charm Payments pages should not use **"hustle."** Charm Cards pages should not open with heavy compliance language.

## WHAT TO NEVER DO

- Never create a new CSS class that duplicates an existing design token / utility.
- Never use `style={{ color: '...' }}` for brand colors — use CSS variables or Tailwind `brand-*` classes.
- Marketing nav is a **mega-nav** (see `charm-payments.mdc` / `Navbar.tsx`): **Products** and **Solutions** use dropdown panels; **Pricing** and **Contact** are direct links. Do not replace this with a flat-only link list.
- Never use **more than 2 font weights** on a single card or section (400 body + 700 heading).
- Never stack two **`btn-accent`** buttons — one accent CTA per section maximum.
- Never put the **compliance disclaimer inside a hero** — it belongs in the **footer** and below pricing sections only.
